### ========================================
### NOTES
### ========================================
#
# IMPORTANT - Authentication Required:
# All endpoints require JWT authentication. Follow these steps:
#
# 1. START AuthService first:
#    cd AuthService && dotnet run
#    (Runs on http://localhost:5170)
#
# 2. START CustomerOrder API:
#    cd CustomerOrder && dotnet run
#    (Runs on http://localhost:5044)
#
# 3. LOGIN to get JWT token:
#    - Run request #0 (Login to get JWT Token)
#    - Copy the "token" value from the response
#    - Paste it in the @token variable (line 22)
#    - OR use AuthService.http to login separately
#
# 4. TEST API endpoints with the token
#
# Available Demo Users:
# - john.doe@example.com / password123 (Customer)
# - jane.smith@example.com / password123 (Customer)
# - bob.johnson@example.com / password123 (Customer)
# - admin@example.com / admin123 (Admin)
#
# Test Execution Order (Recommended):
#
# 1. Run request 0 to get JWT token
# 2. Run requests 1-3 to create customers
# 3. Run request 6 to verify all customers created
# 4. Run requests 13-17 to create orders (all created with "Pending" status)
# 5. Run requests 20-24 to test order retrieval
# 6. Run requests 25-31 to update order status
# 7. Run requests 32-45 to test order filtering and pagination
# 8. Run request 9 to test customer update
# 9. Run request 11 to test customer deletion (optional)
#
# Order Status Workflow:
# - All orders are created with "Pending" status automatically
# - Use PUT /api/orders/{orderNumber} to update status to:
#   * Confirmed
#   * Shipped
#   * Delivered
#   * Cancelled
# - You can also update shipping address during status update
#
# Expected Results:
# - Request 0: 200 OK with JWT token
# - Requests without valid token: 401 Unauthorized
# - Requests 1-3: 201 Created with customer response
# - Requests 4-5: 400 Bad Request with validation errors
# - Request 6: 200 OK with array of customers
# - Requests 13-17: 200 OK with order number (status always "Pending")
# - Request 18: 400 Bad Request (customer not found)
# - Request 19: 400 Bad Request (missing required fields)
# - Requests 25-29: 200 OK with success message
# - Request 30: 404 Not Found (order doesn't exist)
# - Request 31: 400 Bad Request (missing required status field)
# - Filtering requests: 200 OK with filtered/paginated results
#
# Tips:
# - Token expires in 60 minutes - run login again if expired
# - Replace ORDER_NUMBER in requests 22, 25-31 with actual order number from create response
# - Use different ports if running via HTTPS (https://localhost:7223)
# - Check response headers for Location header after POST requests
# - Monitor pagination metadata in filter responses
# - Order status can only be updated, not set during creation
#
#
### ========================================
### GDPR & AUDIT LOGGING NOTES
### ========================================
#
# GDPR Compliance Test Guide:
# ---------------------------
#
# 1. GDPR Article 20 - Right to Data Portability (Requests 46-48)
#    - Export endpoint returns JSON file with all customer data
#    - Includes: personal info, orders, consents
#    - File name format: customer-data-{email}-{date}.json
#    - Expected: 200 OK with downloadable JSON file
#
# 2. GDPR Article 7 - Consent Management (Requests 49-62)
#    - Grant consent: POST /api/customers/{email}/consents
#    - Revoke consent: DELETE /api/customers/{email}/consents/{type}
#    - View consents: GET /api/customers/{email}/consents
#    - Consent types: Marketing, DataProcessing, Profiling, ThirdPartySharing
#    - Tracks: IP address, user agent, consent version, timestamps
#    - Expected: 201 Created for grant, 200 OK for revoke/view
#
# 3. GDPR Article 17 - Right to Erasure (Requests 63-72)
#    - Anonymization endpoint: POST /api/customers/{email}/anonymize
#    - Soft delete: Sets IsDeleted=true, keeps orders intact
#    - Anonymizes: FirstName → "REDACTED", LastName → "REDACTED"
#    - Email → "deleted-{GUID}@anonymized.local"
#    - PhoneNumber → empty
#    - Records: DeletedAt timestamp, DeletedReason
#    - Expected: 200 OK with anonymization confirmation
#    - Prevents: Re-anonymization (returns 400 Bad Request)
#
# 4. GDPR Article 30 - Audit Logging (Automatic)
#    - All API requests are automatically logged via AuditMiddleware
#    - Logs stored in: customerorder.AuditLogs table
#    - Captured data:
#      * Who: UserEmail (from JWT)
#      * What: EntityType, EntityId, Action
#      * When: ActionDate (UTC)
#      * Where: IpAddress
#      * How: HttpMethod, Endpoint, UserAgent
#    - Actions tracked: Created, Updated, Deleted, Viewed, Exported, Anonymized, ConsentGranted, ConsentRevoked
#
# 5. Complete GDPR Workflow (Requests 73-80)
#    - Creates customer → Grants consents → Creates orders → Exports data
#    - Revokes consent → Exports again → Anonymizes
#    - Demonstrates full GDPR lifecycle
#
# Testing Audit Logging:
# ----------------------
# Audit logs are created automatically. To verify:
#
# 1. Run any GDPR endpoint (e.g., request 46 - Export)
# 2. Query the database:
#    SELECT TOP 10 * FROM customerorder.AuditLogs
#    ORDER BY ActionDate DESC;
#
# 3. Verify log contains:
#    - EntityType: "Customer"
#    - EntityId: "john.doe@example.com"
#    - Action: "Exported"
#    - UserEmail: "jane.smith@example.com" (from JWT)
#    - IpAddress: Your local IP
#    - HttpMethod: "GET"
#    - Endpoint: "/api/customers/john.doe@example.com/export"
#
# 4. Check consent actions:
#    SELECT * FROM customerorder.AuditLogs
#    WHERE Action IN ('ConsentGranted', 'ConsentRevoked')
#    ORDER BY ActionDate DESC;
#
# 5. Check anonymization actions:
#    SELECT * FROM customerorder.AuditLogs
#    WHERE Action = 'Anonymized'
#    ORDER BY ActionDate DESC;
#
# Data Retention Service:
# -----------------------
# Background service runs daily at 2 AM UTC (configurable)
#
# Configuration in appsettings.json:
# {
#   "DataRetention": {
#     "DeletedCustomersRetentionDays": 90,
#     "AuditLogRetentionYears": 3,
#     "RunCleanupAtHour": 2,
#     "EnableAutomaticCleanup": true
#   }
# }
#
# Cleanup tasks:
# - Purges audit logs older than 3 years
# - Permanently deletes customers anonymized >90 days ago
# - Logs all operations with counts
#
# To verify data retention in database:
#
# 1. Check anonymized customers (soft deleted):
#    SELECT * FROM customerorder.Customers
#    WHERE IsDeleted = 1
#    ORDER BY DeletedAt DESC;
#
# 2. Check old audit logs:
#    SELECT COUNT(*) FROM customerorder.AuditLogs
#    WHERE ActionDate < DATEADD(YEAR, -3, GETUTCDATE());
#
# 3. Check consents:
#    SELECT c.Email, cc.ConsentType, cc.IsGranted, cc.ConsentDate, cc.RevokedDate
#    FROM customerorder.CustomerConsents cc
#    JOIN customerorder.Customers c ON cc.CustomerId = c.CustomerId
#    ORDER BY cc.ConsentDate DESC;
#
# Expected Results:
# -----------------
# Request 46-47: 200 OK, downloads JSON file
# Request 48: 404 Not Found
# Request 49-52: 201 Created with consent confirmation
# Request 53: 404 Not Found (customer doesn't exist)
# Request 54: 201 Created (duplicate consent allowed)
# Request 55: 400 Bad Request (missing required field)
# Request 56-57: 200 OK with array of consents
# Request 58: 404 Not Found
# Request 59-60: 200 OK with revocation confirmation
# Request 61-62: 404 Not Found
# Request 63-67: Setup for anonymization test
# Request 68: 200 OK with anonymization confirmation
# Request 69: 404 Not Found (customer anonymized)
# Request 70: 400 Bad Request (already deleted)
# Request 71: 404 Not Found
# Request 72: 200 OK
# Request 73-80: Complete GDPR workflow demonstration
#
# GDPR Compliance Verification Checklist:
# ----------------------------------------
# ✅ Article 7 (Consent): Can grant, view, and revoke consents
# ✅ Article 17 (Erasure): Can anonymize customer data
# ✅ Article 20 (Portability): Can export all data as JSON
# ✅ Article 30 (Records): All actions automatically logged
# ✅ Data Retention: Automatic cleanup of old data
# ✅ Soft Delete: Maintains referential integrity
# ✅ Audit Trail: Complete history of data access/modifications
#
# Database Migration Required:
# ----------------------------
# Before testing GDPR endpoints, run:
#   cd CustomerOrder
#   dotnet ef database update
#
# This creates:
# - customerorder.AuditLogs table
# - customerorder.CustomerConsents table
# - Adds soft delete fields to Customers table
#
# Security Notes:
# ---------------
# - All GDPR endpoints require JWT authentication
# - IP address and User-Agent captured for consent tracking
# - Anonymization is irreversible (email becomes GUID)
# - Orders remain intact after customer anonymization
# - Consents are cascade-deleted when customer is hard-deleted
# - Audit logs are append-only (no updates/deletes except retention policy)
#
#
